column237: They are all very baseline guidelines. They would help, if properly followed, to establish some basics but the issues I see go deeper. There must be active work to foster deep community activities. People don't make friends meeting with strangers once. They need continued connection such that the relationships have time to form and be able to stand alone. All of these guidelines do not address that. They are surfsce level.

column237: So much of what is damaging to people with respect to social connection is structural, and a consequence of neoliberal capitalism in all its structural violence and aggression.  Social isolation is not a problem for an individual to solve.  We can't individualize our way out of these problems.  So many hurting people feel alone and like failures already.  Our approaches need to be communitarian, political, policy oriented and definitely about social action together to build community connections.

column237: Society is so broken. Covid fractured an already avoidant, standooffish, selfish, egocentric society. If you show friendliness people shun you. I try so hard...without success. I am in several counseling groups (funded) and am told I am doing everything I need to do...but they agree connections are extremely hard to find. Some community connection places (seniors drop in centers) are worse than nothing because they are full of people who just get together and complain. Younger generations are not taught to respect older generations. People in general are rude to seniors... I am disabled and every time I am out people nearly trip me pushing to rush wherever they are going. I do not believe in age segregation. Even when one joins community classes (I go to at least 3 a month) everyone goes to do the activities but go back home without building connections. Social media and Covid did most damage.

column237: I think that the idea of community died years ago. At best I know my neighbors and we exchange pleasantries, and they would help in an emergency. But the 50s picket fence idealistic image of a block community doesn't exist outside of established hoa style suburbia. All my neighbors rent, and we all experience the same struggles of barely being able to pay rent. These normalized struggles just aren't conducive to establishing longterm relationships, and when we are all barely living a simple "Hi how are ya" in the hall is the closest to a sense of community we can get.

column237: Guidelines are great if implemented properly. Difficult to reach the lonely and the vulnerable when they spend most of their time at home. Social Media needs to be the first tool to reach enough people. Implementing consistent and easily accessible mental health care is a must. Wait times are atrocious and people are feeling more and more like a discarded number, causing further isolation. In the state of the current economy, people are doing less and less due to affordability. Communities need to consider these things when creating space to connect.

column237: I think there are great and very basic to understand. The problem is people. Most people seem to be very selfish and have created the loneliness problem. Then people like me who try to be a genuine and reliable friend end up as collateral damage because others don't know how to behave properly - responding to messages in a timely fashion, not cancelling plans last minute, actually being present when socializing (not spending all the time on one's phone), being able to handle constructive criticism.  People basically need to just stop being gigantic social potatoes if we want to tackle the loneliness issue.

column237: The community guidelines are excellent but require political will and investment.  That is why I'm not sure they are achievable in all communities, although they'd be beneficial in all.  Finite amounts mind you, so what spending stops to make way for these guidelines, and how foundational/important are the supports/services that are currently being funded?  Likely pretty important.  The personal guidelines are much more achievable as they are primarily a matter of personal choice or willpower.

column237: I think these are excellent guidelines, firmly grounded in social determinants of health. I remember completing this survey last year while I was extremely depressed and struggling with intense social isolation; it was wonderful to see how my responses have changed this year and I was delighted that much of how I got to where I am now was by taking steps just like those outlined in your guidelines for individuals. I imagine I could have gotten here a little faster if I'd had access to this list a year ago!

column237: When reading and rereading the variables, I am not convinced that I would benefit from all these guidelines without true person-to-person help, as I experience great difficulty becoming better engaged with aspects of socializing because I think I am rather "outside" of the normative mixture of interactions and ways toward building strong allies. You have to recognize as well that self perception - plus or minus, better or worse - contains many challenging and fluid, ontological & existential nuances............Largely I feel quite lost at my age to be able to find a way to build anything significant for the future of my social self, given my financial burdens, and doing it by myself - in so saying.

column237: Given our current socio-political environment, I'm not convinced that governments and their agencies have the leadership nor ability to act on such guidelines (guidelines not being mandatory or even enforceable).  The community guidelines should be written in a way that include measurable outcomes such that tracking progress is possible and demonstrable.  My fear is that Social Guidelines would receive no more attention than the social determinants of health which, while clearly important to health and wellbeing, are rarely the focus of discussion.  The current political rhetoric and political/social movements in our society and, more specifically from our neighbours to the south, where the focus is on ultra right-wing, populist, anti-science thinking with be a strong force that will run afoul of these social guidelines.  I'm not confident that any government, social agency or health expert/authority will have the impact to move society and the negative thoughts, behaviours and anxiety that result from these right-wing movements.  That said, I believe it is important to push forward with this kind of work while being realistic about how difficult it will be in the face of our current socio-political envirnment.

column237: Transportation is key. Since my husband  died 4years ago I am no longer mobile and have to depend on family to take me shopping,library,etc.  The nearest bus stop is a 20 minute walk ,which in the climate of the North Island means  frequently arriving soaked to wherever you are going. I have been trying to have the bus service extended by a mile,for 4 years,still no success.Government services need to respond in a timely manner, 1/2 dozen people who would have utilized the service have had to move away ,leaving friends/family behind in order to access medical and other se4vices. I could volunteer a lot more if I had  the daily bus route extended along my road

column237: They are all great, and make absolute sense.  They are great to keep in mind when life feels “off the rails” at times.  It would be great to make the guidelines into a matrix or checklist to make it easy to do a self-assessment.   The trouble with all “healthy guidelines” is they are great for people who are already pretty healthy.  Education for young people, especially young parents, teenagers, people with engrained mental health issues or attachment disorders need very specific training in the areas of socialization, actual ways of communication, reading body language and knowing how to self-assess.

column237: I find that my Community has a long way to go to make our environment conducive to social activities for seniors in community.  Benches in parks are spaced far apart and facing away from other people.  It's hard to get a conversation going or even start an impromptu board game or card game.  Safety in my community has dropped dramatically for seniors who have been taken advantage of, attacked and robbed or even pushed in front of a city bus.  I am nervous when I am out side and walking.  It didn't used to be like this and the more people struggle with financial difficulties and hopelessness and homelessness they start to blame others especially seniors because some seniors own their own places where they reside and are living a comfortable lifestyle.

column237: As an introvert, who is extremely content with my life and level of social activity that I participate in, I do think introverts need to be taken into account with these guidelines. Not everyone wants to make the effort to socialize with everyone in their lives on a daily basis, and we don’t need to do so to be happy! For example, My work is separate from my personal and social life; I don’t want to hang out with my coworkers outside of work because that means we end up talking about work when I’m not working, Even though I get along fine with my coworkers (and love my job). Introverts don’t need to be socializing daily to be happy! For example I’ve been off work sick for the entire week and isolated/quarantined by choice to not infect other people, And am able to amuse myself quite well. Introverts with high confidence levels love being by themselves and seek opportunities to do so, we purposely limit our social interactions to avoid exhaustion. So I actually need several days a week of just being by myself, working alone from home, and limiting interactions with other people including neighbours I see in the elevator etc.

column237: Great guidelines, I liked the personal guidelines on how to reduce negative self-talk. As part of the project, I'd like to see more detailed "5 things you can try" for each of them, so people have a more concrete starting point. Right now the guidelines are mostly phrased as targets, which highlights what to aim for, but not always how to get there.  The community pieces did touch on barriers to access (accessible spaces, transit, community spaces) but it was not really addressed by the individual pieces. My neighborhood is part university, part rich housing; both are conservative, religious, and notably apathetic or hostile towards visibly queer people. There are some steps I can take locally, but goals aren't always achievable when you or your family are excluded or ostracized. Add in a reliance on public transport in a car-centric area, any level of fatigue, and it becomes more difficult to reach more welcoming spaces, which again limits ability to be social.  I did like the distinction between communication-focused online activities vs passive social media consumption - Very important. (unfortunately the apps and tools frequently make it difficult to separate - I've gotten off most social media because of how hostile they are to cognition & mental health, but it means I am also less connected to the community.)

column237: I'm a caregiver - my husband is palliative - I'm tied to the house and most of my social interactions are with his caregivers and 3 times a week I have an assisted shower.  He sleeps about 16 hours a day - his hospital bed and various things have taken over the small living/dining room and I eat my meals in my bedroom where I spend most of my day.  We both have access to a tv. When you become a caregiver you are cut off from outside life . We have been married 57 years and I don't want him in a care home - when the times comes (may it be a long ways away) he will pass at home where he belongs.  Also I found it awkward answering questions about work since I'm 76 and I stopped working at 67

column237: I really like them. I was concerned that the tone in the first section (for individuals) was a little judgmental though. It sounded a bit like putting the onus on the individual to address structural problems. I know that is hard to avoid when creating individual recommendations but I also wouldn't want people to think it is 'all their own fault' if they are lonely. Obviously people have to take initiative to help themselves but I would be concerned that those with mental health issues or those who already feel isolated might internalize the wrong message there. Perhaps addressing that possibility might help "If you are used to spending a lot of time alone it can be difficult to join in on social activities or reach out to new people. This is partially a lack of practice! If you feel intimidated, take things slowly and be kind to yourself about the process..." Perhaps specific examples, too?   I really liked the community guideline suggestions and I would love to see communities create 'ambassador' positions specifically to foster social inclusion for lonely people.

column237: Fundamentally I think it doesn't tackle the underlying problems too thoroughly.... a lot of general terms about what to do without the "how". Many of these are difficult skills to learn even if you're aware of the need/willing to learn them/have the resources. Fundamentally I think that the loneliness problem is structural; our communities are designed to take us from our houses to our workplaces or other commercialized/monetized spaces in isolated little boxes (cars) over long distances in relatively high-sprawl communities. While some of the guidelines loosely touch upon this, they're not terribly specific, nor are these issues actually easy to retrofit onto communities with isolating structures. Additionally, I strongly believe that too much work for too little pay is a fundamental underlying issue with our loneliness epidemic. The 40 hour work week is antiquated; it was built on the assumption of an unpaid full-time homemaker, with salaries enough to support the paid and unpaid positions that kept the household running. Now an average salary isn't even enough for one person, many dual-incomes barely scrape by, and the labour that used to be performed by the "homemaker" now has to be outsourced at great expense. I don't think we should be returning to the "traditional" household, but I don't think we can ignore that our work conventions are from another era, and don't even really give us enough time to keep on top of the necessary chores and errands and appointments let alone socializing. And when so many of us lack privacy, especially younger folks who are having to live with parents or many roommates to scrape by, and when there's no public third places and it costs money to be out of the house, and when we're all burned out on scheduling, socialization is nearly impossible. If wages had kept up with productivity and we were able to make a reasonable living working 20-30hrs/wk and had ample places where people could just "go" and expect a social experience without it being commoditized, gamified, externally structured/forced, or hyper-scheduled, we might stand a chance. When we're over-worked, under-paid, functionally having to try and do two full-time jobs (both "breadwinner" and "homemaker")and somehow get in enough rest, over-scheduled, burned-out on logistics, have no privacy and nowhere to go, I don't see a fix. The means and opportunities aren't there. And when you're perpetually exhausted and grumpy and overwhelmed and in survival mode, you can't self-reflect or learn new skills - it's harder to grow socially and harder to form positive social connections/trust others. When the prerequisites for success are nowhere close to being met, telling individuals what to do feels almost patronizing/paternalistic. I think most people WANT to have social connection - I don't think anyone wants to be lonely. I don't think it's that people don't know or aren't trying. I don't think everyone necessarily realizes WHY they struggle so much to find connection, and frankly I think a lot of these guidelines and/or the prerequisites to meet them would be rejected by the extremists a la "15 Minute City" conspiracies, but it doesn't change the fact that you can't meet a goal when you're structurally undermined. IMO this is one of the primary reasons most people can't follow most health guidelines; we're too busy surviving moment-to-moment. Without stability we can't slow down and start thinking longer-term or preventative. We have no spare time or effort left to give past basic survival and sometimes we're not even meeting basic survival. We need capacity freed up before these guidelines are actionable.

column237: Honestly, the personal ones feel a bit tone-deaf for those with time constraints. As an example, I'm a parent of a three year old, working a full time high mental effort job, and living without car ownership (although I do have access to car shares and public transport).  I'm also an introvert and neurodiverse.  Telling me that I need to allocate yet more mental energy to fostering connections in a life that's already so full to capacity that I'm desperate for downtime is not helpful.  Honestly, I think you may want to try capturing the other side of the coin from isolation as well -- how many people are feeling overburdened with social demands?  Are there patterns in gender, age, and other demographics?  Likewise on the community front, I feel some automatic bristle as I envision these guidelines ending up disproportionately handed off to female-presenting persons.  There is a lot of mental load involved in generating and maintaining social connection that is not seemingly appreciated in the guidelines.

column237: The socioeconomic factors of isolation and social disconnection are not focused on nearly enough. What you're promoting are bandaid solutions to profound economic instability and exploitation. Promoting social health programs sounds great on paper but is useless without a strong healthcare system, good jobs, a safe and clean environment, and freedom from abject economic exploitation. Social wellbeing is inherently political and decontextualising it in this way is reductive and unhelpful. Poor people have higher rates of mental illness for a reason.

column237: Following these guidelines would definitely be valuable to all involved. However, there are many factors that require extra funding beyond a usually tight budget. Are larger communities already incorporating this line item in their budgets? If so, I’m betting that their society will see a decrease in many negative activities within the community. But more taxes to the citizens could counter the positive effects unless they fully understand and can see evidence of their ‘ROI’.  I’ve dreamed of designing and creating spaces where people could participate in a variety of social activities within a natural environment, no matter where or when. I am fully aware that I cannot even fathom the amount of investment for such a space to be open and accessible for everyone, no matter where or when. That being said, warring with depression myself, I can imagine the community that could develop when surrounded all things creative and of creation.

column237: I don't think increased awareness would help, as I think most people understand the importance of socialization, except for possibly teenagers/pre-teens. I think increased FREE social activities would really help, because many require you to pay, and because you can't always trust strangers, it can be scary and sometimes unsafe to strike up conversation with random people i.e. on the bus (although this isn't always the case, and I've had some lovely conversations with those on the bus, as well as some very unpleasant ones). I think providing practical tips for incorporating even small amounts of social interaction would be helpful too (i.e. "try to eat together", or "try to commute/carpool" etc). Other tips like "get enough sleep" and "eat well" because I find I often don't feel like socializing when I'm low energy from not enough food and/or sleep.

Human connection is very needed and valued and we should strive to keep it in our lives as much as possible.

column237: Communities coming together to implement these healthy social connections guidelines would be difficult since many communities are separated as cultural silos and cultural enclaves with different levels of de factor cultural tribalistic segregation happening as well as the fact that many communities do not have active neighborhood groups or active neighborhood watches where most people get along smoothly. Many communities tend to also be dominated by others and there's still underlying issues of language differences, language barriers, cultural differences, cultural barriers, and different forms and levels of ethnic discrimination, language discrimination, religious discrimination and religious barriers, different types of racisms (anti-Black racism, anti-Caribbean racism, anti-African racism, anti-Indian racism, anti-Asian racism, etc), cultural discrimination, and different types of cultural superiority complexes (i.e.: some people feeling their language and culture is better than others), negative biases against groups, negative stereotyping, negative racial profiling between different groups that might also happen to reside in close proximity or in the same neighborhood area. Forming healthy social connections can be different when people are culturally divided or culturally isolated and when there are language barriers, ethnic barriers, racial barriers, and different active forms of discrimination still existing in a neighborhood or in a community. Forming community programs that are inclusive, fair, balanced, civil, healthy, and diverse can also be challenging in neighborhoods with a lot of ethnic differences and language differences. People typically stick to themselves, or stick to their own families and stick to their own cultural groups and language groups, because it is easier, simpler, and sometimes even socially safer to do so (even if it isn't ideal).

So then it falls on individuals within the community to organize and champion this. Most of us are struggling to ensure we stay in touch with our own network of friends and family so can't imagine taking it on, as much as I totally agree with the concept.
